{"title_page": "Filipino mestizo", "text_new": "<!--When adding additional information, please make sure it is unbiased, easy to understand, and verifiable.-->\n<!--Please refer to people of purely Spanish descent as \"Spaniards\" to maintain clarity and consistency throughout the article.-->\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Filipino mestizo\n|image      = Jose rizal 01.jpg\n|caption    = The ancestral record of Philippine National Hero [[Jos\u00e9 Rizal]] himself includes [[Spanish Filipino|Spanish]], [[Chinese Filipino|Chinese]] and [[Japanese people|Japanese]] blood.\n|population =\n|regions    = [[Philippines]], [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Spain]]\n|languages  = [[Languages of the Philippines|Philippine languages]], [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n|religions  = Predominantly [[Christianity in the Philippines|Christianity]]<br>([[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic]] majority, [[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestant]] minority) and [[Islam|Muslim]] minority\n|related-c  = Other [[Filipinos]], various other [[ethnic groups]]\n}}\n{{Demographics of the Philippines}}\n[[File:Mestizos, detail from Carta Hydrographica y Chorographica de las Yslas Filipinas (1734).jpg|thumb|Mestizos as illustrated in the ''[[Carta Hydrographica y Chorographica de las Yslas Filipinas]]'', 1734]]\nIn the [[Philippines]], '''Filipino mestizo''' or colloquially '''''tisoy''''', are people of mixed [[Filipinos|Filipino]] and any foreign ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mestizo|title=Mestizo - Define Mestizo at Dictionary.com|work=Dictionary.com}}</ref> The word [[mestizo]] itself is of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] origin; it was first used in the [[Americas]] to describe only people of mixed [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] and European ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Mestizo|title=Mestizo - Define Mestizo at Dictionary.com|work=Dictionary.com}}</ref> An estimated 5 million people of mixed Spanish and Filipino heritage live in the [[Philippines]].<ref> https://nl.pinterest.com/schelingen/spanish-culture-and-heritage-in-the-philippines-a-/</ref> They represent 5% of its total population.\n\n== History ==\n\n===Spanish period===\n{{main article|Spanish Filipino}}\n{{see also|Philippine Spanish}}\nThe [[Spain|Spanish]] expedition in 1565, prompted a period of Spanish colonization over the Philippines which lasted for 333 years. The Roman Catholic Church played an important role in allowing Spanish settlements in the Philippines. The Spanish government and religious missionaries were quick to learn native Filipino languages and Roman Catholic rituals were interpreted in accordance with Filipino beliefs and values. As a result, a folk Roman Catholicism developed in the Philippines.<ref name=\"Philippine History\">{{cite web|url=http://asia.msu.edu/seasia/Philippines/History/hist_spanish.html|title=Asian Studies Center \u2013 Michigan State University \u2013 Oops!|author=International Studies & Programs at Michigan State University|work=msu.edu|access-date=2007-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009235201/http://asia.msu.edu/seasia/Philippines/History/hist_spanish.html|archive-date=2007-10-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> European settlers from Spain and Mexico immigrated and their offspring (of either [[Spanish people|Spanish]], or Spanish and Filipino) may have adopted the culture of their parents and grandparents. Most Filipinos of Spanish descent in the Philippines are of mixed ancestries or are of pure European ancestry.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\nSome individuals still speak Spanish in the country, in addition, [[Chavacano]] (a [[creole language]] based largely on the Spanish vocabulary) is widely spoken in the Southern Philippines, including the [[Zamboanga Peninsula]] and its neighbouring regions. Spanish era periodicals record that as much as one third of the inhabitants of the island of Luzon possess varying degrees of Spanish admixture.<ref>F\u00ebdor Jagor et al. (1870). [http://www.authorama.com/former-philippines-b-8.html ''The Former Philippines thru Foreign Eyes'']</ref> In addition to Luzon, select cities such as [[Bacolod City|Bacolod]], [[Cebu City|Cebu]], [[Iloilo City|Iloilo]] or [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]] which are home to historical military fortifications or commercial ports during the Spanish era also holds sizable mestizo communities.<ref>[http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html Quinze Ans de Voyage Autor de Monde Vol. II ( 1840)]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009181632/http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html |date=2014-10-09 }}. Retrieved 2014-7-25 from [http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html/ Institute for Research of Iloilo Official Website]  .</ref>\n\n===Chinese immigration===\n{{Main article|Sangley}}\n{{See also|Chinese Filipino}}\nEven before Spanish arrived in the Philippines, the Chinese have traded with the natives of the Philippines. During the colonial period, there was an increase in the number of Chinese immigrants into the Philippines. The Spaniards restricted the activities of the Chinese and confined them to the [[Pari\u00e1n]] which was located near [[Intramuros]]. Most of the Chinese residents earned their livelihood as traders.\n\nMany of the Chinese who arrived during the Spanish period were Cantonese, who worked as labourers, but there were also Fujianese, who entered the retail trade. The Chinese resident in the islands were encouraged to intermarry with Filipinos, convert to Roman Catholicism and adopt Hispanic names, surnames and customs through the ''[[Cat\u00e1logo alfab\u00e9tico de apellidos]]'' introduced by the Spaniards in the mid-19th century.\n\nDuring the [[United States]] colonial period, the [[Chinese Exclusion Act]] of the United States was also applied to the Philippines.<ref name=\"the Chinese Exclusion Act\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenagain.info/WebChron/USA/ChineseExclusion.html|title=Chinese Exclusion Act: 1882|work=thenagain.info}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[World War II in the Philippines|Second World War]] and the victory of the [[Communist Party of China|Communists]] in the [[Chinese Civil War]], many refugees who fled from Mainland China settled in the Philippines. This group formed the bulk of the current population of Chinese Filipinos.<ref name=\"Filipino Chinese\">{{cite web |url=http://filipino-chinese.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2&Itemid=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017130623/http://filipino-chinese.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2&Itemid=1 |archivedate=2007-10-17 }}</ref> After the Philippines achieved full sovereignty on 4 July 1946, Chinese immigrants became naturalised Filipino citizens, while the children of these new citizens who were born in the country acquired [[Filipino citizen]]ship from birth.<ref name=\"From Sangley to Chinoy\">{{cite web|url=http://pinoykasi.homestead.com/files/2001articles/08052001_From_Sangley.htm|title=Website Disabled|work=homestead.com}}</ref>\n\nChinese Filipinos are one of the largest [[overseas Chinese]] communities in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=\"ocac.gov.tw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ocac.gov.tw/download.asp?tag%3DP%26file%3DDownFile%2FFile_17979.pdf%26no%3D17979 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018051535/http://www.ocac.gov.tw/download.asp?tag=P&file=DownFile%2FFile_17979.pdf&no=17979 |archivedate=October 18, 2013 }}</ref> [[Sangley]]s\u2014Filipinos with at least some Chinese ancestry \u2014 comprise 18\u201327% of the Philippine population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.wur.nl/WebQuery/clc/587677 |title=Sangley, Intsik und Sino : die chinesische Haendlerminoritaet in den Philippine}}</ref> There are roughly 1.5 million Filipinos with pure Chinese ancestry, or about 1.6% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://summit.sfu.ca/system/files/iritems1/6689/b1744892x.pdf |title=The ethnic Chinese variable in domestic and foreign policies in Malaysia and Indonesia |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Colonial caste system==\nThe history of racial mixture in the Philippines occurred on a smaller scale than other [[Spanish Empire|Spanish territories in Americas]] during the Spanish colonial period from the 16th to the 19th century. This [[ethno-religious]] social stratification schema was similar to the ''[[casta]]'' system used in [[Hispanic America]], with some major differences.\n\nThe system was used for taxation purposes, with ''indios'' and ''negritos'' who lived within the colony paying a base tax, ''mestizos de sangley'' paying double the base tax, ''sangleys'' paying quadruple; ''blancos'', however, paid no tax. The caste system was abolished after the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] from Spain in 1898, and the term ''Filipino'' was expanded to include the entire population of the Philippines regardless of racial ancestry. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Term\n! Definition\n! Image\n|-\n| [[Negrito]]\n| person of pure [[Aeta]] ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Malay race|Indio]]\n| person of pure [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]] ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Chinese |Chino]]\n| person of pure Chinese ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Chinese Filipino|Mestizo de Sangley]]\n| person of mixed Chinese and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Indian Filipino|Mestizo de Bombay]]\n| person of mixed Indian and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n|  [[Spanish Filipino|Mestizo de Espa\u00f1ol]]\n| person of mixed Spanish and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Torna atr\u00e1s|Tornatr\u00e1s]]\n| person of mixed Spanish, Austronesian and Chinese ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Spanish people|Filipino/Insulares]]\n| person of pure Spanish descent born in the Philippines\n|\n|-\n| Americano\n| person of [[Criollo people|Criollo]] (either pure Spanish blood, or mostly), [[castizo]] (1/4 Native American, 3/4 Spanish) or [[mestizo]] (1/2 Spanish, 1/2 Native American) descent born in Spanish America (\"from the Americas\")\n|\n|-\n| [[Peninsulares]]\n| person of pure Spanish descent born in Spain (\"from the [[Iberian Peninsula]]\")\n|\n|}\n[[File:Diversity of Philippines.jpg|thumb|A native Filipina with Chinese, European and Japanese settlers in the Philippines, 1900]]\nThe Spanish deliberately implemented incentives to entangle the various races together to stop rebellion:<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8yc0AAAAIAAJ|title=Historical Conservation Society|publisher=The Society.|year=1963|page=191}}</ref><ref name=\"Mas19632\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=22gKAQAAIAAJ|title=Informe secreto de Sinibaldo de M\u00e1s|author=Sinibaldo De Mas|publisher=Historical Conservation Society|year=1963|page=191}}</ref><ref name=\"Liao19642\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vrDkAAAAIAAJ|title=Chinese participation in Philippine culture and economy|author=Shubert S. C. Liao|publisher=Bookman|year=1964|page=30}}</ref>\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = El Mestiso by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = ''El Mestiso'' (A Filipino Mestizo) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n| image2 = La Mestisa by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| caption2 = ''La Mestisa'' (A Filipina Mestiza) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n}}{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = La Mestisa Espa\u00f1ola by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = ''La Mestisa Espa\u00f1ola'' (A Spanish Filipina Mestiza) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n| image2 = Mestizos Sangley y Chino by Justiano Asuncion.jpg\n| caption2 = ''Mestizos Sangley y Chino'' ([[Sangley]] Chinese-Filipino Mestizos) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n}}<blockquote>\n\"It is needful to encourage public instruction in all ways possible, permit newspapers subject to a liberal censure, to establish in Manila a college of medicine, surgery, and pharmacy: in order to break down the barriers that divide the races, and amalgamate them all into one. For that purpose, the Spaniards of the country, the Chinese mestizos, and the Filipinos shall be admitted with perfect equality as cadets of the military corps; the personal-service tax shall be abolished, or an equal and general tax shall be imposed, to which all the Spaniards shall be subject. This last plan appears to me more advisable, as the poll-tax is already established, and it is not opportune to make a trial of new taxes when it is a question of allowing the country to be governed by itself. Since the annual tribute is unequal, the average shall be taken and shall be fixed, consequently, at fifteen or sixteen reals per whole tribute, or perhaps one peso fuerte annually from each adult tributary person. This regulation will produce an increase in the revenue of 200,000 or 300,000 pesos fuertes, and this sum shall be set aside to give the impulse for the amalgamation of the races, favoring crossed marriages by means of dowries granted to the single women in the following manner. To a Chinese mestizo woman who marries a Filipino shall be given 100 pesos; to a Filipino woman who marries a Chinese mestizo, Ioo pesos; to a Chinese mestizo woman who marries a Spaniard, 1,000 pesos; to a Spanish woman who marries a Chinese mestizo, 2,000 pesos; to a Filipino woman who marries a Spaniard, 2,000 pesos; to a Spanish woman who marries a Filipino chief, 3,000 or 4,000 pesos. Some mestizo and Filipino alcaldes-mayor of the provinces shall be appointed. It shall be ordered that when a Filipino chief goes to the house of a Spaniard, he shall seat himself as the latter's equal. In a word, by these and other means, the idea that they and the Castilians are two kinds of distinct races shall be erased from the minds of the natives, and the families shall become related by marriage in such manner that when free of the Castilian dominion should any exalted Filipinos try to expel or enslave our race, they would find it so interlaced with their own that their plan would be practically impossible.\"<ref name=\"Blair19152\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FrJEAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA86|title=The Philippine Islands, 1493\u20131898: Relating to China and the Chinese|author=Emma Helen Blair|publisher=A.H. Clark Company|year=1915|pages=85\u201387}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = [[Spanish Filipino]]\n| image =Filipino woman 2.jpg\n| caption = Spanish-Filipina mestiza wearing the traditional [[Mar\u00eda Clara gown]] of the Philippines and the long hair tradition of the Filipina women during the colonial era\n| population = \n| regions = [[Philippines]]\n| languages = [[Filipino language|Filipino]], [[languages of the Philippines|other Philippine languages]], [[English language|English]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].\n| religions = [[Christianity in the Philippines|Christianity]] ([[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholicism]], and [[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestantism]].)\n| related-c = [[Filipino people]], Filipino Mestizos\n}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Chinese Filipino<br> \u83ef\u83f2\u4eba <br> ''Intsik''<br> ''Pilipinong Tsino''\n| image = Chinese Filipino.jpg\n| image_caption = Chinese-Filipina girl wearing the [[Mar\u00eda Clara gown]], the traditional gown of Filipina women\n| pop = At least '''1.5 million''' are of pure Chinese ancestry.\n| popplace = [[Metro Manila]], [[Baguio]], [[Central Visayas]], [[Metro Iloilo-Guimaras]], [[Metro Davao]]<br/>[[Negros (Philippines)|Negros]], [[Pangasinan]], [[Pampanga]], [[Tarlac]], [[Cagayan de Oro]]<br/>[[Vigan]], [[Laoag]], [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Rizal (province)|Rizal]], [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena]], [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga]], [[Zamboanga City]], [[Sulu (province)|Sulu]]\n| langs = [[Filipino language|Filipino]], [[Philippine English|English]] and other [[languages of the Philippines]]<br> [[Philippine Hokkien|Hokkien]], [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Standard Cantonese|Cantonese]], [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]], [[Hakka Chinese]], various other [[varieties of Chinese]]\n| rels = [[Christianity]] ([[Roman Catholicism]], [[Protestantism]], [[Philippine Independent Church|P.I.C]], [[Iglesia ni Cristo]]), [[Buddhism]], [[Islam]], [[Daoism]]\n| related = [[Sangley]], [[Overseas Chinese]]\n}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = American settlement in the Philippines\n| image = Filipino American family.jpg\n| caption = Filipino-American family, Philippines\n| popplace = [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles City]]{{\u00b7}}[[Baguio]]{{\u00b7}}[[San Fernando, La Union]]{{\u00b7}}[[Calamba, Laguna|Calamba]]{{\u00b7}}[[Tuguegarao]]{{\u00b7}}[[Calapan]]{{\u00b7}}[[Legazpi, Albay|Legazpi]]{{\u00b7}}[[Iloilo City|Iloilo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Olongapo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Pagadian]]{{\u00b7}}[[Cagayan de Oro]]{{\u00b7}}[[Davao City|Davao]]{{\u00b7}}[[Koronadal]]{{\u00b7}}[[Butuan]]{{\u00b7}}[[Cotabato City|Cotabato]]{{\u00b7}}[[Metro Cebu]]{{\u00b7}}[[Metro Manila]]\n| langs = [[Filipino language|Filipino]]{{\u00b7}}[[American English]]{{\u00b7}}[[Philippine English]]\n| rels = [[Protestantism]]{{\u00b7}}[[Roman Catholicism]]{{\u00b7}}[[Buddhism]]\n| related = [[Americans]] (especially [[White Americans]])\n}}\n\nPersons classified as ''blancos'' (whites) were subdivided into the ''peninsulares'' (persons of pure Spanish descent born ''in Spain''); ''insulares'' or ''filipinos'' (persons of pure Spanish descent born ''in the Philippines'' i.e. [[Criollo people|criollos]]); ''mestizos de espa\u00f1ol'' (persons of mixed Autronesian and Spanish ancestry), and ''tornatr\u00e1s'' (persons of mixed Austronesian, Chinese, and Spanish ancestry).\n\nPersons of pure Spanish descent living in the Philippines who were born in Hispanic America were classified as ''americanos''. Mestizos and [[mulatto]]es born in Hispanic America living in the Philippines kept their legal classification as such, and usually came as indentured servants to the ''americanos''. The Philippine-born children of ''americanos'' were classified as ''filipinos''. Philippine-born children of mestizos and mulattoes from Hispanic America were classified based on patrilineal descent.\n\nThe [[indigenous peoples of the Philippines]] were referred to as ''Indios'' (for those of pure Austronesian descent) and [[negrito]]s. ''Indio'' was a general term applied to native Austronesians as a legal classification; it was only applied to Christianised natives who lived in proximity to the Spanish colonies. Persons who lived outside of Manila, Cebu, and areas with a large Spanish concentration were classified as such: ''naturales'' were baptised Austronesians of the lowland and coastal towns. Unbaptised Austronesians and Aetas who lived in the towns were classified as ''salvajes'' (savages) or ''infieles'' (infidels). ''Remontados'' (\"those who went to the mountains\") and ''tulisanes'' (bandits) were Austronesians and Aetas who refused to live in towns and moved upland. They were considered to live outside the social order as [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Catholicism]] was a driving force in everyday life as well as determinant of social class.\n\nThe Spanish legally classified the Aetas as ''negritos'', based on their appearance. The word term would be misinterpreted and used by future European scholars as an ethnoracial term in and of itself. Both Christianised Aetas who lived in the colony and unbaptised Aetas who lived in tribes outside of the colony were classified ''negrito''. Christianised Aetas who lived in Manila were not allowed to enter Intramuros and lived in areas designated for ''indios''. Persons of Aeta descent were also viewed as being outside the social order as they usually lived in tribes beyond settlements and resisted conversion to Christianity.\n\nThe fluid nature of racial integration in the Philippines during the Spanish colonial period was recorded by many travelers and public figures at the time, who were favorably impressed by the lack of racial discrimination, as compared to the situation in other European colonies.\n\nAmong them was Sir [[John Bowring]], Governor General of British Hong Kong and a well-seasoned traveler who had written several books about the different cultures in Asia. He described the situation as \"admirable\" during a visit to the Philippines in the 1870s:\n<blockquote>\nThe lines separating entire classes and races, appeared to me less marked than in the Oriental colonies. I have seen on the same table, Spaniards, Mestizos (Chinos cristianos) and Indios, priests and military. There is no doubt that having one Religion forms great bonding. And more so to the eyes of one that has been observing the repulsion and differences due to race in many parts of Asia. And from one (like myself) who knows that race is the great divider of society, the admirable contrast and exception to racial discrimination so markedly presented by the people of the Philippines is indeed admirable.<ref>Chester L. Hunt (1954) ''Sociology in the Philippine setting: A modular approach'', p. 118, Phoenix Pub. House</ref>\n</blockquote>\nAnother foreign witness was English engineer, Frederic H. Sawyer, who had spent most of his life in different parts of Asia and lived in Luzon for fourteen years. His impression was that as far as racial integration and harmony was concerned, the situation in the Philippines was not equaled by any other colonial power:\n<blockquote>\n\"... Spaniards and natives lived together in great harmony, and do not know where I could find a colony in which Europeans mixes as much socially with the natives. Not in Java, where a native of position must dismount to salute the humblest Dutchman. Not in British India, where the Englishwoman has now made the gulf between British and native into a bottomless pit.\"<ref>Frederic H. Sawyer (1900) [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/38081/38081-h/38081-h.htm ''The Inhabitants of the Philippines''], p. 125, New York.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Modern term and usage==\n{{Redirect|Tisoy|the 2019 tropical cyclone named by [[PAGASA]] as \"Tisoy\"|Typhoon Kammuri (2019)}}\nToday, the word ''mestizo'' is shortened as ''tisoy'' just as is the word [[Pinoy]] for Filipino. It is used for all Filipinos with foreign ancestry, particularly those born in the diaspora or as children of recent immigrants.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Filipino people of Spanish ancestry]]\n*[[Template:Miscegenation in Spanish Philippines]]\n*[[Demographics of the Philippines]]\n*[[Ethnic groups in the Philippines]]\n;Comparisons with other countries\n*[[Casta]] (comparable caste system in [[Latin America]])\n*[[Indo people]] of Indonesia\n*[[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]]\n*[[Amerasian]]\n*[[Afro-Asian]]\n*[[Multiracial]]\n*[[Template:Miscegenation in Spanish colonies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Wickberg, Edgar. (March 1964) \"[http://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/dspace/bitstream/1808/1129/1/CEAS.1964.n10.pdf The Chinese Mestizo in Philippine History]\". ''The Journal of Southeast Asian History, 5(1)'', 62\u2013100. Lawrence, Kansas: The University of Kansas, CEAS.\n*Monroy, Emily. (23 August 2002) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090715083913/http://www.analitica.com/Bitblio/emily_monroy/race_mixing.asp Race Mixing and Westernization in Latin America and the Philippines]\". ''analitica.com''. Caracas, Venezuela.\n*Gambe, Annabelle R. (2000) ''Overseas Chinese Entrepreneurship and Capitalist Development in Southeast Asia''. M\u00fcnster, Hamburg and Berlin: LIT Verlag.\n*Anderson, Benedict. (1988) ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20081003035607/http://www.public-conversations.org.za/_pdfs/anderson_12.pdf  Cacique Democracy in the Philippines: Origins and Dreams]''.\n*Weightman, George H. (February 1960) ''The Philippine Chinese: A Cultural History of A Marginal Trading Company''. Ann Arbor, Michigan: UMI Dissertation Information Service.\n*Tettoni, Luca Invernizzi and Sosrowardoyo, Tara. (1997). Filipino Style. ''Periplus Editions Ltd.'' Hong Kong, China.\n*Tan, Hock Beng. (1994). Tropical Architecture and Interiors. ''Page One Publishing Pte Ltd.'' Singapore.\n*[https://whc.unesco.org/archive/advisory_body_evaluation/502rev.pdf  Advisory Body Evaluation] (1999). ''UNESCO World Heritage Site''.\n*Medina, Elizabeth. (1999) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20070209232520/http://xeniaeditrice.it/lens.pdf Thru the Lens of Latin America: A Wide-Angle View of the Philippine Colonial Experience]\". Santiago, Chile.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070927092857/http://www.seacex.es/documentos/imag_colonial_13_identidad.pdf The Colonial Imaginary. Photography in the Philippines during the Spanish Period 1860\u20131898] (2006). ''Casa Asia: Centro Cultural Conde Duque''. Madrid, Spain.\n*Blair, E. H. and Robertson, J.A. (editors). (1907) [https://www.fulltextarchive.com/page/History-of-the-Philippine-Islands-Vols-1-and1/ History of the Philippine Islands Vols. 1 and 2] by Dr. Antonio de Morga (Translated and Annotated in English). ''The Arthur H. Clark Company''. Cleveland, Ohio.\n*Craig, Austin. (2004). [https://books.google.com/books?id=SdMMBza_e38C&printsec=frontcover Lineage, Life and Labors of Jose Rizal, Philippine Patriot]. ''Kessinger Publishing''. Whitefish, Montana.\n*[http://www.popline.org/docs/0010/016619.html Culture and fertility: the case of the Philippines]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{Mestizos}}\n{{Multiethnicity}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish Philippines]]\n[[Category:Philippine society]]\n[[Category:European colonisation in Asia]]\n[[Category:Multiracial affairs in Asia]]\n[[Category:European diaspora in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Filipino people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Mestizo]]\n", "text_old": "<!--When adding additional information, please make sure it is unbiased, easy to understand, and verifiable.-->\n<!--Please refer to people of purely Spanish descent as \"Spaniards\" to maintain clarity and consistency throughout the article.-->\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n|group      = Filipino mestizo\n|image      = Jose rizal 01.jpg\n|caption    = The ancestral record of Philippine National Hero [[Jos\u00e9 Rizal]] himself includes [[Spanish Filipino|Spanish]], [[Chinese Filipino|Chinese]] and [[Japanese people|Japanese]] blood.\n|population =\n|regions    = [[Philippines]], [[United States]], [[Canada]], [[Spain]]\n|languages  = [[Languages of the Philippines|Philippine languages]], [[English language|English]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n|religions  = Predominantly [[Christianity in the Philippines|Christianity]]<br>([[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholic]] majority, [[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestant]] minority) and [[Islam|Muslim]] minority\n|related-c  = Other [[Filipinos]], various other [[ethnic groups]]\n}}\n{{Demographics of the Philippines}}\n[[File:Mestizos, detail from Carta Hydrographica y Chorographica de las Yslas Filipinas (1734).jpg|thumb|Mestizos as illustrated in the ''[[Carta Hydrographica y Chorographica de las Yslas Filipinas]]'', 1734]]\nIn the [[Philippines]], '''Filipino mestizo''' or colloquially '''''tisoy''''', are people of mixed [[Filipinos|Filipino]] and any foreign ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mestizo|title=Mestizo - Define Mestizo at Dictionary.com|work=Dictionary.com}}</ref> The word [[mestizo]] itself is of [[Spanish language|Spanish]] origin; it was first used in the [[Americas]] to describe only people of mixed [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] and European ancestry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/Mestizo|title=Mestizo - Define Mestizo at Dictionary.com|work=Dictionary.com}}</ref> An estimated 5 million people of mixed Spanish and Filipino heritage live in the [[Philippines]].<ref> https://nl.pinterest.com/schelingen/spanish-culture-and-heritage-in-the-philippines-a-/</ref> They represent 5% of its total population.\n\n== History ==\n\n===Spanish period===\n{{main article|Spanish Filipino}}\n{{see also|Philippine Spanish}}\nThe [[Spain|Spanish]] expedition in 1565, prompted a period of Spanish colonization over the Philippines which lasted for 333 years. The Roman Catholic Church played an important role in allowing Spanish settlements in the Philippines. The Spanish government and religious missionaries were quick to learn native Filipino languages and Roman Catholic rituals were interpreted in accordance with Filipino beliefs and values. As a result, a folk Roman Catholicism developed in the Philippines.<ref name=\"Philippine History\">{{cite web|url=http://asia.msu.edu/seasia/Philippines/History/hist_spanish.html|title=Asian Studies Center \u2013 Michigan State University \u2013 Oops!|author=International Studies & Programs at Michigan State University|work=msu.edu|access-date=2007-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009235201/http://asia.msu.edu/seasia/Philippines/History/hist_spanish.html|archive-date=2007-10-09|url-status=dead}}</ref> European settlers from Spain and Mexico immigrated and their offspring (of either [[Spanish people|Spanish]], or Spanish and Filipino) may have adopted the culture of their parents and grandparents. Most Filipinos of Spanish descent in the Philippines are of mixed ancestries or are of pure European ancestry.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\nSome individuals still speak Spanish in the country, in addition, [[Chavacano]] (a [[creole language]] based largely on the Spanish vocabulary) is widely spoken in the Southern Philippines, including the [[Zamboanga Peninsula]] and its neighbouring regions. Spanish era periodicals record that as much as one third of the inhabitants of the island of Luzon possess varying degrees of Spanish admixture.<ref>F\u00ebdor Jagor et al. (1870). [http://www.authorama.com/former-philippines-b-8.html ''The Former Philippines thru Foreign Eyes'']</ref> In addition to Luzon, select cities such as [[Bacolod City|Bacolod]], [[Cebu City|Cebu]], [[Iloilo City|Iloilo]] or [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]] which are home to historical military fortifications or commercial ports during the Spanish era also holds sizable mestizo communities.<ref>[http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html Quinze Ans de Voyage Autor de Monde Vol. II ( 1840)]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009181632/http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html |date=2014-10-09 }}. Retrieved 2014-7-25 from [http://ilongo.weebly.com/iloilo-history-part-5.html/ Institute for Research of Iloilo Official Website]  .</ref>\n\n===Chinese immigration===\n{{Main article|Sangley}}\n{{See also|Chinese Filipino}}\nEven before Spanish arrived in the Philippines, the Chinese have traded with the natives of the Philippines. During the colonial period, there was an increase in the number of Chinese immigrants into the Philippines. The Spaniards restricted the activities of the Chinese and confined them to the [[Pari\u00e1n]] which was located near [[Intramuros]]. Most of the Chinese residents earned their livelihood as traders.\n\nMany of the Chinese who arrived during the Spanish period were Cantonese, who worked as labourers, but there were also Fujianese, who entered the retail trade. The Chinese resident in the islands were encouraged to intermarry with Filipinos, convert to Roman Catholicism and adopt Hispanic names, surnames and customs through the ''[[Cat\u00e1logo alfab\u00e9tico de apellidos]]'' introduced by the Spaniards in the mid-19th century.\n\nDuring the [[United States]] colonial period, the [[Chinese Exclusion Act]] of the United States was also applied to the Philippines.<ref name=\"the Chinese Exclusion Act\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenagain.info/WebChron/USA/ChineseExclusion.html|title=Chinese Exclusion Act: 1882|work=thenagain.info}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[World War II in the Philippines|Second World War]] and the victory of the [[Communist Party of China|Communists]] in the [[Chinese Civil War]], many refugees who fled from Mainland China settled in the Philippines. This group formed the bulk of the current population of Chinese Filipinos.<ref name=\"Filipino Chinese\">{{cite web |url=http://filipino-chinese.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2&Itemid=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-12-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017130623/http://filipino-chinese.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2&Itemid=1 |archivedate=2007-10-17 }}</ref> After the Philippines achieved full sovereignty on 4 July 1946, Chinese immigrants became naturalised Filipino citizens, while the children of these new citizens who were born in the country acquired [[Filipino citizen]]ship from birth.<ref name=\"From Sangley to Chinoy\">{{cite web|url=http://pinoykasi.homestead.com/files/2001articles/08052001_From_Sangley.htm|title=Website Disabled|work=homestead.com}}</ref>\n\nChinese Filipinos are one of the largest [[overseas Chinese]] communities in [[Southeast Asia]].<ref name=\"ocac.gov.tw\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ocac.gov.tw/download.asp?tag%3DP%26file%3DDownFile%2FFile_17979.pdf%26no%3D17979 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=February 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018051535/http://www.ocac.gov.tw/download.asp?tag=P&file=DownFile%2FFile_17979.pdf&no=17979 |archivedate=October 18, 2013 }}</ref> [[Sangley]]s\u2014Filipinos with at least some Chinese ancestry \u2014 comprise 18\u201327% of the Philippine population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.wur.nl/WebQuery/clc/587677 |title=Sangley, Intsik und Sino : die chinesische Haendlerminoritaet in den Philippine}}</ref> There are roughly 1.5 million Filipinos with pure Chinese ancestry, or about 1.6% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://summit.sfu.ca/system/files/iritems1/6689/b1744892x.pdf |title=The ethnic Chinese variable in domestic and foreign policies in Malaysia and Indonesia |format=PDF |accessdate=2012-04-23}}</ref>\n\n==Colonial caste system==\nThe history of racial mixture in the Philippines occurred on a smaller scale than other [[Spanish Empire|Spanish territories in Americas]] during the Spanish colonial period from the 16th to the 19th century. This [[ethno-religious]] social stratification schema was similar to the ''[[casta]]'' system used in [[Hispanic America]], with some major differences.\n\nThe system was used for taxation purposes, with ''indios'' and ''negritos'' who lived within the colony paying a base tax, ''mestizos de sangley'' paying double the base tax, ''sangleys'' paying quadruple; ''blancos'', however, paid no tax. The caste system was abolished after the [[Philippine Declaration of Independence]] from Spain in 1898, and the term ''Filipino'' was expanded to include the entire population of the Philippines regardless of racial ancestry. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Term\n! Definition\n! Image\n|-\n| [[Negrito]]\n| person of pure [[Aeta]] ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Malay|Indio]]\n| person of pure [[Austronesian peoples|Austronesian]] ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Chinese |Chino]]\n| person of pure Chinese ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Chinese Filipino|Mestizo de Sangley]]\n| person of mixed Chinese and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Indian Filipino|Mestizo de Bombay]]\n| person of mixed Indian and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n|  [[Spanish Filipino|Mestizo de Espa\u00f1ol]]\n| person of mixed Spanish and Austronesian ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Torna atr\u00e1s|Tornatr\u00e1s]]\n| person of mixed Spanish, Austronesian and Chinese ancestry\n|\n|-\n| [[Peninsulares|Filipino/Insulares]]\n| person of pure Spanish descent born in the Philippines\n|\n|-\n| Americano\n| person of [[Criollo people|Criollo]] (either pure Spanish blood, or mostly), [[castizo]] (1/4 Native American, 3/4 Spanish) or [[mestizo]] (1/2 Spanish, 1/2 Native American) descent born in Spanish America (\"from the Americas\")\n|\n|-\n| [[Peninsulares]]\n| person of pure Spanish descent born in Spain (\"from the [[Iberian Peninsula]]\")\n|\n|}\n[[File:Diversity of Philippines.jpg|thumb|A native Filipina with Chinese, European and Japanese settlers in the Philippines, 1900]]\nThe Spanish deliberately implemented incentives to entangle the various races together to stop rebellion:<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8yc0AAAAIAAJ|title=Historical Conservation Society|publisher=The Society.|year=1963|page=191}}</ref><ref name=\"Mas19632\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=22gKAQAAIAAJ|title=Informe secreto de Sinibaldo de M\u00e1s|author=Sinibaldo De Mas|publisher=Historical Conservation Society|year=1963|page=191}}</ref><ref name=\"Liao19642\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vrDkAAAAIAAJ|title=Chinese participation in Philippine culture and economy|author=Shubert S. C. Liao|publisher=Bookman|year=1964|page=30}}</ref>\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = El Mestiso by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = ''El Mestiso'' (A Filipino Mestizo) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n| image2 = La Mestisa by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| caption2 = ''La Mestisa'' (A Filipina Mestiza) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n}}{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| total_width = 300\n| image1 = La Mestisa Espa\u00f1ola by Justiniano Asuncion.jpg\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = ''La Mestisa Espa\u00f1ola'' (A Spanish Filipina Mestiza) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n| image2 = Mestizos Sangley y Chino by Justiano Asuncion.jpg\n| caption2 = ''Mestizos Sangley y Chino'' ([[Sangley]] Chinese-Filipino Mestizos) by [[Justiniano Asuncion]], c. 1841\n}}<blockquote>\n\"It is needful to encourage public instruction in all ways possible, permit newspapers subject to a liberal censure, to establish in Manila a college of medicine, surgery, and pharmacy: in order to break down the barriers that divide the races, and amalgamate them all into one. For that purpose, the Spaniards of the country, the Chinese mestizos, and the Filipinos shall be admitted with perfect equality as cadets of the military corps; the personal-service tax shall be abolished, or an equal and general tax shall be imposed, to which all the Spaniards shall be subject. This last plan appears to me more advisable, as the poll-tax is already established, and it is not opportune to make a trial of new taxes when it is a question of allowing the country to be governed by itself. Since the annual tribute is unequal, the average shall be taken and shall be fixed, consequently, at fifteen or sixteen reals per whole tribute, or perhaps one peso fuerte annually from each adult tributary person. This regulation will produce an increase in the revenue of 200,000 or 300,000 pesos fuertes, and this sum shall be set aside to give the impulse for the amalgamation of the races, favoring crossed marriages by means of dowries granted to the single women in the following manner. To a Chinese mestizo woman who marries a Filipino shall be given 100 pesos; to a Filipino woman who marries a Chinese mestizo, Ioo pesos; to a Chinese mestizo woman who marries a Spaniard, 1,000 pesos; to a Spanish woman who marries a Chinese mestizo, 2,000 pesos; to a Filipino woman who marries a Spaniard, 2,000 pesos; to a Spanish woman who marries a Filipino chief, 3,000 or 4,000 pesos. Some mestizo and Filipino alcaldes-mayor of the provinces shall be appointed. It shall be ordered that when a Filipino chief goes to the house of a Spaniard, he shall seat himself as the latter's equal. In a word, by these and other means, the idea that they and the Castilians are two kinds of distinct races shall be erased from the minds of the natives, and the families shall become related by marriage in such manner that when free of the Castilian dominion should any exalted Filipinos try to expel or enslave our race, they would find it so interlaced with their own that their plan would be practically impossible.\"<ref name=\"Blair19152\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FrJEAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA86|title=The Philippine Islands, 1493\u20131898: Relating to China and the Chinese|author=Emma Helen Blair|publisher=A.H. Clark Company|year=1915|pages=85\u201387}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = [[Spanish Filipino]]\n| image =Filipino woman 2.jpg\n| caption = Spanish-Filipina mestiza wearing the traditional [[Mar\u00eda Clara gown]] of the Philippines and the long hair tradition of the Filipina women during the colonial era\n| population = \n| regions = [[Philippines]]\n| languages = [[Filipino language|Filipino]], [[languages of the Philippines|other Philippine languages]], [[English language|English]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]].\n| religions = [[Christianity in the Philippines|Christianity]] ([[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Roman Catholicism]], and [[Protestantism in the Philippines|Protestantism]].)\n| related-c = [[Filipino people]], Filipino Mestizos\n}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Chinese Filipino<br> \u83ef\u83f2\u4eba <br> ''Intsik''<br> ''Pilipinong Tsino''\n| image = Chinese Filipino.jpg\n| image_caption = Chinese-Filipina girl wearing the [[Mar\u00eda Clara gown]], the traditional gown of Filipina women\n| pop = At least '''1.5 million''' are of pure Chinese ancestry.\n| popplace = [[Metro Manila]], [[Baguio]], [[Central Visayas]], [[Metro Iloilo-Guimaras]], [[Metro Davao]]<br/>[[Negros (Philippines)|Negros]], [[Pangasinan]], [[Pampanga]], [[Tarlac]], [[Cagayan de Oro]]<br/>[[Vigan]], [[Laoag]], [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], [[Rizal (province)|Rizal]], [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena]], [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga]], [[Zamboanga City]], [[Sulu (province)|Sulu]]\n| langs = [[Filipino language|Filipino]], [[Philippine English|English]] and other [[languages of the Philippines]]<br> [[Philippine Hokkien|Hokkien]], [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Standard Cantonese|Cantonese]], [[Teochew dialect|Teochew]], [[Hakka Chinese]], various other [[varieties of Chinese]]\n| rels = [[Christianity]] ([[Roman Catholicism]], [[Protestantism]], [[Philippine Independent Church|P.I.C]], [[Iglesia ni Cristo]]), [[Buddhism]], [[Islam]], [[Daoism]]\n| related = [[Sangley]], [[Overseas Chinese]]\n}}\n\n{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = American settlement in the Philippines\n| image = Filipino American family.jpg\n| caption = Filipino-American family, Philippines\n| popplace = [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles City]]{{\u00b7}}[[Baguio]]{{\u00b7}}[[San Fernando, La Union]]{{\u00b7}}[[Calamba, Laguna|Calamba]]{{\u00b7}}[[Tuguegarao]]{{\u00b7}}[[Calapan]]{{\u00b7}}[[Legazpi, Albay|Legazpi]]{{\u00b7}}[[Iloilo City|Iloilo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Olongapo]]{{\u00b7}}[[Pagadian]]{{\u00b7}}[[Cagayan de Oro]]{{\u00b7}}[[Davao City|Davao]]{{\u00b7}}[[Koronadal]]{{\u00b7}}[[Butuan]]{{\u00b7}}[[Cotabato City|Cotabato]]{{\u00b7}}[[Metro Cebu]]{{\u00b7}}[[Metro Manila]]\n| langs = [[Filipino language|Filipino]]{{\u00b7}}[[American English]]{{\u00b7}}[[Philippine English]]\n| rels = [[Protestantism]]{{\u00b7}}[[Roman Catholicism]]{{\u00b7}}[[Buddhism]]\n| related = [[Americans]] (especially [[White Americans]])\n}}\n\nPersons classified as ''blancos'' (whites) were subdivided into the ''peninsulares'' (persons of pure Spanish descent born ''in Spain''); ''insulares'' or ''filipinos'' (persons of pure Spanish descent born ''in the Philippines'' i.e. [[Criollo people|criollos]]); ''mestizos de espa\u00f1ol'' (persons of mixed Autronesian and Spanish ancestry), and ''tornatr\u00e1s'' (persons of mixed Austronesian, Chinese, and Spanish ancestry).\n\nPersons of pure Spanish descent living in the Philippines who were born in Hispanic America were classified as ''americanos''. Mestizos and [[mulatto]]es born in Hispanic America living in the Philippines kept their legal classification as such, and usually came as indentured servants to the ''americanos''. The Philippine-born children of ''americanos'' were classified as ''filipinos''. Philippine-born children of mestizos and mulattoes from Hispanic America were classified based on patrilineal descent.\n\nThe [[indigenous peoples of the Philippines]] were referred to as ''Indios'' (for those of pure Austronesian descent) and [[negrito]]s. ''Indio'' was a general term applied to native Austronesians as a legal classification; it was only applied to Christianised natives who lived in proximity to the Spanish colonies. Persons who lived outside of Manila, Cebu, and areas with a large Spanish concentration were classified as such: ''naturales'' were baptised Austronesians of the lowland and coastal towns. Unbaptised Austronesians and Aetas who lived in the towns were classified as ''salvajes'' (savages) or ''infieles'' (infidels). ''Remontados'' (\"those who went to the mountains\") and ''tulisanes'' (bandits) were Austronesians and Aetas who refused to live in towns and moved upland. They were considered to live outside the social order as [[Catholic Church in the Philippines|Catholicism]] was a driving force in everyday life as well as determinant of social class.\n\nThe Spanish legally classified the Aetas as ''negritos'', based on their appearance. The word term would be misinterpreted and used by future European scholars as an ethnoracial term in and of itself. Both Christianised Aetas who lived in the colony and unbaptised Aetas who lived in tribes outside of the colony were classified ''negrito''. Christianised Aetas who lived in Manila were not allowed to enter Intramuros and lived in areas designated for ''indios''. Persons of Aeta descent were also viewed as being outside the social order as they usually lived in tribes beyond settlements and resisted conversion to Christianity.\n\nThe fluid nature of racial integration in the Philippines during the Spanish colonial period was recorded by many travelers and public figures at the time, who were favorably impressed by the lack of racial discrimination, as compared to the situation in other European colonies.\n\nAmong them was Sir [[John Bowring]], Governor General of British Hong Kong and a well-seasoned traveler who had written several books about the different cultures in Asia. He described the situation as \"admirable\" during a visit to the Philippines in the 1870s:\n<blockquote>\nThe lines separating entire classes and races, appeared to me less marked than in the Oriental colonies. I have seen on the same table, Spaniards, Mestizos (Chinos cristianos) and Indios, priests and military. There is no doubt that having one Religion forms great bonding. And more so to the eyes of one that has been observing the repulsion and differences due to race in many parts of Asia. And from one (like myself) who knows that race is the great divider of society, the admirable contrast and exception to racial discrimination so markedly presented by the people of the Philippines is indeed admirable.<ref>Chester L. Hunt (1954) ''Sociology in the Philippine setting: A modular approach'', p. 118, Phoenix Pub. House</ref>\n</blockquote>\nAnother foreign witness was English engineer, Frederic H. Sawyer, who had spent most of his life in different parts of Asia and lived in Luzon for fourteen years. His impression was that as far as racial integration and harmony was concerned, the situation in the Philippines was not equaled by any other colonial power:\n<blockquote>\n\"... Spaniards and natives lived together in great harmony, and do not know where I could find a colony in which Europeans mixes as much socially with the natives. Not in Java, where a native of position must dismount to salute the humblest Dutchman. Not in British India, where the Englishwoman has now made the gulf between British and native into a bottomless pit.\"<ref>Frederic H. Sawyer (1900) [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/38081/38081-h/38081-h.htm ''The Inhabitants of the Philippines''], p. 125, New York.</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Modern term and usage==\n{{Redirect|Tisoy|the 2019 tropical cyclone named by [[PAGASA]] as \"Tisoy\"|Typhoon Kammuri (2019)}}\nToday, the word ''mestizo'' is shortened as ''tisoy'' just as is the word [[Pinoy]] for Filipino. It is used for all Filipinos with foreign ancestry, particularly those born in the diaspora or as children of recent immigrants.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Filipino people of Spanish ancestry]]\n*[[Template:Miscegenation in Spanish Philippines]]\n*[[Demographics of the Philippines]]\n*[[Ethnic groups in the Philippines]]\n;Comparisons with other countries\n*[[Casta]] (comparable caste system in [[Latin America]])\n*[[Indo people]] of Indonesia\n*[[Eurasian (mixed ancestry)|Eurasian]]\n*[[Amerasian]]\n*[[Afro-Asian]]\n*[[Multiracial]]\n*[[Template:Miscegenation in Spanish colonies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Wickberg, Edgar. (March 1964) \"[http://kuscholarworks.ku.edu/dspace/bitstream/1808/1129/1/CEAS.1964.n10.pdf The Chinese Mestizo in Philippine History]\". ''The Journal of Southeast Asian History, 5(1)'', 62\u2013100. Lawrence, Kansas: The University of Kansas, CEAS.\n*Monroy, Emily. (23 August 2002) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20090715083913/http://www.analitica.com/Bitblio/emily_monroy/race_mixing.asp Race Mixing and Westernization in Latin America and the Philippines]\". ''analitica.com''. Caracas, Venezuela.\n*Gambe, Annabelle R. (2000) ''Overseas Chinese Entrepreneurship and Capitalist Development in Southeast Asia''. M\u00fcnster, Hamburg and Berlin: LIT Verlag.\n*Anderson, Benedict. (1988) ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20081003035607/http://www.public-conversations.org.za/_pdfs/anderson_12.pdf  Cacique Democracy in the Philippines: Origins and Dreams]''.\n*Weightman, George H.